('cmcd3ez4r003uyjleiaa2wsz3', 'cmc0apnf90038qoublubz4128', 'Nvidia is again the world''s most valuable company', 'In June 2025, Nvidia once again became the most valuable publicly traded company in the world, surpassing Microsoft and Apple. The company''s stock rose by more than 4%, reaching a record high of $154.31, which pushed its market capitalization to $3.77 trillion. This marks the second time in a month that Nvidia has overtaken its rivals in total market value.\\n\\nAt the annual shareholders meeting, CEO Jensen Huang reaffirmed the company''s strategic focus on artificial intelligence and robotics. He emphasized that the Nvidia Drive platform will be fundamental to the transition toward software-defined vehicles and highlighted the importance of this transformation in the near future.\\n\\nDespite export restrictions on H20 AI chips to China—which may cost the company around $8 billion in the second quarter—investor confidence remains strong. Huang described the export bans as a setback that, in his view, only accelerated technological advancement within China itself. In the most recent fiscal year, Nvidia generated $17.1 billion in revenue from China, accounting for 13.1% of its total and representing a 66% increase year-over-year.\\n\\nSince the beginning of 2025, Nvidia shares have gained nearly 15%. Investors continue to view the company as a key player in the development of AI, automotive electronics, and cloud computing, despite geopolitical risks and export limitations. Nvidia''s leadership is reinforced not only by its innovation in chips, but also by its role in shaping the technological landscape of the future.', 'image', 'Tech', 'https://iwzfrnfemdeomowothhn.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/posts/images/thumb_342ebd8f8ae33060249217910c90fdf0.webp', 'https://iwzfrnfemdeomowothhn.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/posts/342ebd8f8ae33060249217910c90fdf0.webp', false, false, NULL, 'SOL', 2, 0, 0, '2025-06-26 07:59:55.996', '2025-06-26 17:56:59.987'),

('cmcd355or003qyjlerq1uqpaf', 'cmc0apnf90038qoublubz4128', 'Kawasaki''s Robotic Goat: The Future of Off-Road Mobility', 'In 2022, Kawasaki surprised the tech world by unveiling Bex — a four-legged robot inspired by the alpine ibex. Unlike most robotic animals built for military or warehouse use, Bex combines advanced engineering with a playful, almost whimsical design. It can walk on four legs, roll on wheels, and carry up to 100 kg of cargo — or even a person.\\n\\nDeveloped by Kawasaki''s RHP (Robotics, Humanoid Platform) team, Bex features a hybrid locomotion system. On flat terrain, it switches to wheels for greater efficiency. When it encounters rough ground, it shifts into walking mode, mimicking nature''s own approach. It''s controlled via handlebars, making the ride on this mechanical goat both functional and slightly futuristic.\\n\\nBex is designed for multiple purposes: transporting cargo through hard-to-reach areas, personal mobility, and serving as a development platform for advanced robotic systems. It also showcases Kawasaki''s engineering capabilities and hints at future applications in rescue operations, agriculture, and research.\\n\\nAlthough still a prototype, Bex represents Kawasaki''s vision to blend robotics, mobility, and innovation into one unexpected package.', 'image', 'Tech', 'https://iwzfrnfemdeomowothhn.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/posts/images/thumb_85d308ce10c6fa6701fe023bdf25104b.webp', 'https://iwzfrnfemdeomowothhn.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/posts/85d308ce10c6fa6701fe023bdf25104b.jpg', false, false, NULL, 'SOL', 3, 0, 0, '2025-06-26 07:52:17.931', '2025-06-26 17:57:05.791'),

