('cmcbks37z004evwbrsuvtz7kg', 'cmbvtqy84000gqowpvlo2r5tp', 'Pikes Peak Hill Climb: Race to the Clouds', 'The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb, held annually in Colorado since 1916, is one of the most thrilling and dangerous races in the world. Drivers race 12.42 miles (20 km) up to the summit of Pikes Peak, reaching an altitude of 4,302 meters (14,115 feet). With 156 tight turns, steep cliffs, and rapidly changing weather, it''s a battle against nature, gravity, and machine.\\n\\nFor decades, much of the course was gravel, adding to the danger. It wasn''t fully paved until 2012, but the challenge remains legendary. Racers bring everything from motorcycles and rally cars to electric prototypes.\\n\\nAmong the first legends was Walter Röhrl, who in 1987 became the first driver to finish in under 11 minutes in an Audi Sport Quattro S1, showcasing the power of all-wheel drive. In 1988, Ari Vatanen delivered a stunning performance in a Peugeot 405 T16, captured in the short film Climb Dance.\\n\\nIn 2013, Sébastien Loeb shattered records in a Peugeot 208 T16, clocking an 8:13.878. That record was broken in 2018 by Romain Dumas in the all-electric Volkswagen I.D. R, with a time of 7:57.148 — proving that the future of racing might be electric.\\n\\nToday, Pikes Peak continues to attract daring drivers and cutting-edge machines. It''s not just a race — it''s a symbol of pushing limits at the edge of the sky.', 'image', 'Tech', 'https://iwzfrnfemdeomowothhn.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/posts/images/thumb_1936c9b10e4e2bc34c97ac6d00ee8aa0.webp', 'https://iwzfrnfemdeomowothhn.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/posts/1936c9b10e4e2bc34c97ac6d00ee8aa0.jpg', false, false, NULL, 'SOL', 2, 0, 0, '2025-06-25 06:30:28.944', '2025-06-25 14:00:58.773'),

